# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fire-alarm-notification-appliance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The **Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990** (**ADA**) (42 U.S.C. § 12101) is a civil rights law that prohibits discrimination based on disability.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] It affords similar protections against discrimination to Americans with disabilities as the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which made discrimination based on race, religion, sex, national origin, and other characteristics illegal, and later sexual orientation and gender identity.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] In addition, unlike the Civil Rights Act, the ADA also requires covered employers to provide reasonable accommodations to employees with disabilities, and imposes accessibility requirements on public accommodations.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] In 1986, the National Council on Disability had recommended the enactment of an Americans with Disabilities Act and drafted the first version of the bill which was introduced in the House and Senate in 1988.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] A broad bipartisan coalition of legislators supported the ADA, while the bill was opposed by business interests (who argued the bill imposed costs on business) and conservative evangelicals (who opposed protection for individuals with HIV).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The final version of the bill was signed into law on July 26, 1990, by President George H.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] It was later amended in 2008 and signed by President George W.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Bush with changes effective as of January 1, 2009.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Conditions classed as disabilities under the ADA include both mental and physical conditions.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] A condition does not need to be severe or permanent to be a disability.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Certain specific conditions that are widely considered anti-social, or tend to result in illegal activity, such as kleptomania, pedophilia, exhibitionism, and voyeurism, are excluded under the definition of "disability" in order to prevent abuse of the statute's purpose.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Additionally, sexual orientation is no longer considered a disorder and is also excluded from the definition of "disability".
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] However, in 2022, the United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit stated that the ADA covers individuals with gender dysphoria, which may aid transgender people in accessing legal protections they otherwise may be unable to.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The ADA states that a "covered entity" shall not discriminate against "a qualified individual with a disability".
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] This applies to job application procedures, hiring, advancement and discharge of employees, job training, and other terms, conditions, and privileges of employment.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] "Covered entities" include employers with 15 or more employees, as well as employment agencies, labor organizations, and joint labor-management committees.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] There are strict limitations on when a covered entity can ask job applicants or employees disability-related questions or require them to undergo medical examination, and all medical information must be kept confidential.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Prohibited discrimination may include, among other things, firing or refusing to hire someone based on a real or perceived disability, segregation, and harassment based on a disability.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Covered entities are also required to provide reasonable accommodations to job applicants and employees with disabilities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] An employer is not required to provide an accommodation that would involve undue hardship (excessive difficulty or expense), and the individual who receives the accommodation must still perform the essential functions of the job and meet the normal performance requirements.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] An employee or applicant who currently engages in the illegal use of drugs is not considered qualified when a covered entity takes adverse action based on such use.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Part of Title I was found unconstitutional by the United States Supreme Court as it pertains to states in the case of *Board of Trustees of the University of Alabama v.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Garrett* as violating the sovereign immunity rights of the several states as specified by the Eleventh Amendment to the United States Constitution.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The Court determined that state employees cannot sue their employer for violating ADA rules.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] State employees can, however, file complaints at the Department of Justice or the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, who can sue on their behalf.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Title II prohibits disability discrimination by all public entities at the local level, e.g., school district, municipal, city, or county, and at state level.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Public entities must comply with Title II regulations by the U.S.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] These regulations cover access to all programs and services offered by the entity.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Access includes physical access described in the ADA Standards for Accessible Design and programmatic access that might be obstructed by discriminatory policies or procedures of the entity.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Title II applies to public transportation provided by public entities through regulations by the U.S.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] It includes the National Railroad Passenger Corporation (Amtrak), along with all other commuter authorities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] This section requires the provision of paratransit services by public entities that provide fixed-route services.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] ADA also sets minimum requirements for space layout in order to facilitate wheelchair securement on public transport.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Title II also applies to all state and local public housing, housing assistance, and housing referrals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The Office of Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity is charged with enforcing this provision.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Under Title III, no individual may be discriminated against on the basis of disability with regards to the full and equal enjoyment of the goods, services, facilities, or accommodations of any place of public accommodation by any person who owns, leases, or operates a place of public accommodation.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Public accommodations include most places of lodging (such as inns and hotels), recreation, transportation, education, and dining, along with stores, care providers, and places of public displays.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Title III also has applications to existing facilities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] One of the definitions of "discrimination" under Title III of the ADA is a "failure to remove" architectural barriers in existing facilities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] This means that even facilities that have not been modified or altered in any way after the ADA was passed still have obligations.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The standard is whether "removing barriers" (typically defined as bringing a condition into compliance with the ADAAG) is "readily achievable", defined as "...easily accomplished without much difficulty or expense".
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The statutory definition of "readily achievable" calls for a balancing test between the cost of the proposed alteration and the wherewithal of the business and/or owners of the business.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Thus, what might be "readily achievable" for a sophisticated and financially capable corporation might not be readily achievable for a small or local business.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] There are exceptions to this title; many private clubs and religious organizations may not be bound by Title III.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Under 2010 revisions of Department of Justice regulations, newly constructed or altered swimming pools, wading pools, and spas must have an accessible means of entrance and exit to pools for disabled people.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] However, the requirement is conditioned on whether providing access through a fixed lift is "readily achievable".
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Other requirements exist, based on pool size, include providing a certain number of accessible means of entry and exit, which are outlined in Section 242 of the standards.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] However, businesses are free to consider the differences in the application of the rules depending on whether the pool is new or altered, or whether the swimming pool was in existence before the effective date of the new rule.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Full compliance may not be required for existing facilities; Section 242 and 1009 of the 2010 Standards outline such exceptions.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The ADA Service Animal Guidelines protect persons with disabilities and their access to public spaces, businesses, and local or state government services.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Representatives for a business or organization are only allowed to ask two questions (1) ask if the animal is a service animal and (2) ask what tasks is the animal trained to perform.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Business representatives are not allowed to ask the service animal to perform the task, request documentation (such as an ID) for the animal, and finally are not allowed to inquire about the nature of the person's disability.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] A service animal cannot be asked to be removed unless either the animal is out of control and their handler cannot get the animal under control (e.g., the dog is barking uncontrollably and cannot be calmed) or if the animal is not housebroken.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] It is worth noting that a service animal is not allowed to be removed or barred from entry even in the case of another patron's allergies or of fear of animals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Businesses that prepare or serve food must allow service animals and their owners on the premises even if state or local health laws would otherwise prohibit animals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Additional protections outlined under the ADA ensures that disabled people and their service animals cannot be isolated from other patrons, treated less favorably than other patrons, or charged fees that are not charged to other patrons without animals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The ADA also specifies that if a business requires a deposit or fee to be paid by patrons with pets, it must waive the charge for service animals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The ADA provides explicit coverage for auxiliary aids.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Captions are considered one type of auxiliary aid.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Since the passage of the ADA, the use of captioning has expanded.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Entertainment, educational, informational, and training materials are captioned for deaf and hard-of-hearing audiences at the time they are produced and distributed.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The **Television Decoder Circuitry Act of 1990** requires that all televisions larger than 13 inches sold in the United States after July 1993 have a special built-in decoder that enables viewers to watch closed-captioned programming.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The Telecommunications Act of 1996 directs the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to adopt rules requiring closed captioning of most television programming.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The FCC's rules on closed captioning became effective January 1, 1998.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Title IV of the ADA amended the Communications Act of 1934 primarily by adding section 47 U.S.C. § 225.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] This section requires that all telecommunications companies in the U.S. take steps to ensure functionally equivalent services for consumers with disabilities, notably those who are deaf or hard of hearing and those with speech impairments.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] When Title IV took effect in the early 1990s, it led to the installation of public teletypewriter (TTY) machines and other TDD (telecommunications devices for the deaf).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Title IV also led to the creation, in all 50 states and the District of Columbia, of what was then called dual-party relay services and now are known as Telecommunications Relay Services (TRS), such as STS relay.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] TRS-mediated calls are made over the Internet by consumers who use broadband connections.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Some are Video Relay Service (VRS) calls, while others are text calls.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] In either variation, communication assistants translate between the signed or typed words of a consumer and the spoken words of others.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] It discusses, for example, the fact that nothing in the ADA amends, overrides or cancels anything in Section 504.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Additionally, Title V includes an anti-retaliation or coercion provision.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The ADA has roots in Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The law began in the Virginia House of Delegates in 1985 as the Virginians with Disabilities Act—supported by Warren G.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Stambaugh—which was passed by the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] It is the first iteration of the Americans with Disabilities Act.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] In 1986, the National Council on Disability (NCD), an independent federal agency, issued a report, Towards Independence, in which the Council examined incentives and disincentives in federal laws towards increasing the independence and full integration of people with disabilities into U.S. society.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Among the disincentives to independence the Council identified was the existence of large remaining gaps in civil rights coverage for people with disabilities in the United States.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] A principal conclusion of the report was to recommend the adoption of comprehensive civil rights legislation, which became the ADA.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The idea of federal legislation enhancing and extending civil rights legislation to millions of Americans with disabilities gained bipartisan support in late 1988 and early 1989.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] In early 1989 both Congress and the newly inaugurated Bush White House worked separately, then jointly, to write legislation capable of expanding civil rights without imposing undue harm or costs on those already in compliance with existing rules and laws.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Over the years, key activists and advocates played an important role in lobbying members of the U.S.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Congress to develop and pass the ADA, including Justin Whitlock Dart Jr., Patrisha Wright and others.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Wright is known as "the General" for her work in coordinating the campaign to enact the ADA.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] She is widely considered the main force behind the campaign lobbying for the ADA.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Senator Bob Dole, who himself had a disability resulting from war injuries, was a vocal supporter and advocate for the bill.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Senators Ted Kennedy and Tom Harkin were the chief sponsors of the bill in the Senate.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Conservative evangelicals opposed the ADA because the legislation protected individuals with HIV, which they associated with homosexuality.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The debate over the Americans with Disabilities Act led some religious groups to take opposite positions.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The Association of Christian Schools International opposed the ADA in its original form, primarily because the ADA labeled religious institutions "public accommodations" and thus would have required churches to make costly structural changes to ensure access for all.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The cost argument advanced by ACSI and others prevailed in keeping religious institutions from being labeled as "public accommodations".
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Church groups such as the National Association of Evangelicals testified against the ADA's Title I employment provisions on grounds of religious liberty.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Many companies, corporations, and business groups opposed the Americans with Disabilities Act, arguing that the legislation would impose costs on businesses.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Pro-business conservative commentators joined in opposition, writing that the Americans with Disabilities Act was "an expensive headache to millions" that would not necessarily improve the lives of people with disabilities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] As the activists did so, many of them chanted "ADA now", and "Vote, Now".
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Some activists who remained at the bottom of the steps held signs and yelled words of encouragement at the "Capitol Crawlers".
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Jennifer Keelan, a second grader with cerebral palsy, was videotaped as she pulled herself up the steps, using mostly her hands and arms, saying "I'll take all night if I have to." This direct action is reported to have "inconvenienced" several senators and to have pushed them to approve the act.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] While there are those who do not attribute much overall importance to this action, the "Capitol Crawl" of 1990 is seen by some present-day disability activists in the United States as a central act for encouraging the ADA into law.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Senator Tom Harkin (D-IA) authored what became the final bill and was its chief sponsor in the Senate.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Harkin delivered part of his introduction speech in sign language, saying it was so his deaf brother could understand.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The ADA defines a covered disability as a physical or mental impairment that substantially limits one or more major life activities, a history of having such an impairment, or being regarded as having such an impairment.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) was charged with interpreting the 1990 law with regard to discrimination in employment.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The EEOC developed regulations limiting an individual's impairment to one that "severely or significantly restricts" a major life activity.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The ADAAA directed the EEOC to amend its regulations and replace "severely or significantly" with "substantially limits", a more lenient standard.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] On September 25, 2008, President George W.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Bush signed the ADA Amendments Act of 2008 (ADAAA) into law.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The amendment broadened the definition of "disability", thereby extending the ADA's protections to a greater number of people.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The act overturned a 1999 US Supreme Court case that held that an employee was not disabled if the impairment could be corrected by mitigating measures; it specifically provides that such impairment must be determined without considering such ameliorative measures.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] It also overturned the court's finding that an impairment that substantially limits one major life activity must also limit others to be considered a disability.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] In October 2019, the Supreme Court declined to resolve a circuit split as to whether websites are covered by the ADA.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The Court turned down an appeal from Domino's Pizza and let stand a U.S.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] 9th Circuit Court of Appeals ruling which held that the Americans with Disabilities Act protects access not just to brick-and-mortar public accommodations, but also to the websites and apps of those businesses.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The ADA led to significant improvements in terms of access to public services, accessibility in the built environment, and societal understanding of disability.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Before the ADA, the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 laid the groundwork for accessibility.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] However, its enforcement was limited to institutions that received federal funding.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The passage of the ADA expanded requirements to encompass state and local institutions.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Between 1991 (after the enactment of the ADA) and 1995, the employment rate of men with disabilities dropped by 7.8% regardless of age, educational level, or type of disability, with the most affected being young, less-educated and intellectually disabled men.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] To these employers, hiring people with disabilities became too expensive as they had to spend extra on assistive technology.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] From 2015 to 2024, employment trends for workers with disabilities showed mixed progress under the ADA.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The unemployment rate for disabled workers also improved.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] It dropped to a low of 7.2% in 2023—a number that it still twice that of nondisabled workers (3.5%).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Policy updates, such as the 2014 Workforce Innovation and Opportunity Act (WIOA), emphasized integrated employment and strengthened affirmative action for federal contractors under Section 503 of the Rehabilitation Act.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Barriers, including wage gaps (disabled workers earned 66 cents for every dollar earned by nondisabled workers in 2023) and Section 14(c) of the Fair Labor Standards Act which allows subminimum wages, have drawn criticism from advocates.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Edward Jay Epstein blamed the act for the replacement of large single-screen movie palaces with multiplexes with many screens.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] According to Epstein, the act imposed wheelchair ramp requirements on new or renovated movie theaters with more than 299 seats, so industry leader AMC Theatres and its competitors evaded this by dividing multiplexes as much as possible into small auditoriums with 299 seats or less.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Then to fill all those seats, exhibitors began to book the same film across multiple screens with showtimes every hour or half hour.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Before the passage of the ADA, disability was perceived as something to be cured or rehabilitated.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Gradually after the passage of the ADA, societal attitudes veered towards addressing impediments to access by people with disabilities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Eventually, disability came to be viewed as a natural part of life that plays a role in positive self-identity.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] However, implicit biases remain within the professional, educational and medical spheres.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Limited training and preconceived notions contribute to high rates of comorbidities;they contribute to lower employment rates and higher rates of arrests.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Since enforcement of the act began in July 1992, it has quickly become a major component of employment law.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] The ADA allows private plaintiffs to receive only injunctive relief (a court order requiring the public accommodation to remedy violations of the accessibility regulations) and attorneys' fees, and does not provide monetary rewards to private plaintiffs who sue non-compliant businesses.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Unless a state law, such as the California Unruh Civil Rights Act, provides for monetary damages to private plaintiffs, persons with disabilities do not obtain direct financial benefits from suing businesses that violate the ADA.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Moreover, there may be a benefit to these private attorneys general who identify and compel the correction of illegal conditions: they may increase the number of public accommodations accessible to persons with disabilities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] "Civil rights law depends heavily on private enforcement.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] However, in states that have enacted laws that allow private individuals to win monetary awards from non-compliant businesses (as of 2008, these include California, Florida, Hawaii, and Illinois), "professional plaintiffs" are typically found.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] At least one of these plaintiffs in California has been barred by courts from filing lawsuits unless he receives prior court permission.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p01] Through the end of fiscal year 1998, 86% of the 106,988 ADA charges filed with and resolved by the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, were either dropped or investigated and dismissed by EEOC but not without imposing opportunity costs and legal fees on employers.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] There have been some notable cases regarding the ADA.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] For example, a major hotel room marketer (Hotels.com) with their business presence on the Internet was sued because their customers with disabilities could not reserve hotel rooms through their website without substantial extra efforts that persons without disabilities were not required to perform.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] Such lawsuits represent a major potential expansion of the ADA in that they (known as "bricks vs. clicks"), seek to expand the ADA's authority to cyberspace, where entities may not have actual physical facilities that are required to comply.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] One of the first major ADA lawsuits, Paralyzed Veterans of America v.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] Ellerbe Becket Architects and Engineers (PVA 1996) was focused on the wheelchair accessibility of a stadium project that was still in the design phase, MCI Center (now known as Capital One Arena) in Washington, D.C.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] Previous to this case, which was filed only five years after the ADA was passed, the DOJ was unable or unwilling to provide clarification on the distribution requirements for accessible wheelchair locations in large assembly spaces.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] While Section 4.33.3 of ADAAG makes reference to lines of sight, no specific reference is made to seeing over standing patrons.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] The MCI Center, designed by Ellerbe Becket Architects & Engineers, was designed with too few wheelchair and companion seats, and the ones that were included did not provide sight lines that would enable the wheelchair user to view the playing area while the spectators in front of them were standing.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] This case and another related case established precedent on seat distribution and sight lines issues for ADA enforcement that continues to present day.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] UPS had no policy to ensure that deaf applicants and employees actually received effective communication in the workplace.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] The outcome was that UPS agreed to pay a $5.8 million settlement and agreed to a comprehensive accommodations program that was implemented in their facilities throughout the country.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] Therefore, under Title II no person with a disability can be unjustly excluded from participation in or be denied the benefits of services, programs or activities of any public entity.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] Importantly, the court held that the defendant need not provide proof that this particular application of the seniority system should prevail, and that, once the defendant showed that the accommodation violated the seniority system, it fell to Barnett to show it was nevertheless reasonable.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] In this case, Barnett was a US Airways employee who injured his back, rendering him physically unable to perform his cargo-handling job.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] Invoking seniority, he transferred to a less-demanding mailroom job, but this position later became open to seniority-based bidding and was bid on by more senior employees.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] Barnett requested the accommodation of being allowed to stay on in the less-demanding mailroom job.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] US Airways denied his request, and he lost his job.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/americans-with-disabilities-act-p02] In 2022, the United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit stated that the ADA covers individuals with gender dysphoria, which may aid transgender people in accessing legal protections they otherwise may be unable to.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/ansi] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Autocall was founded in 1908 by two businessmen from Shelby Electric Company after they witnessed a demonstration of a unique telegraph system in use at a plant for employee communication while on a business trip.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Seeing the need for such a system at their own company, the two designed an automatic version of this system and founded Autocall.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Soon after, the company produced their first 120VAC coded fire alarm system.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1920, an advertisement centered on the infamous Triangle Shirtwaist Factory Fire helped to gain the company significant business and began to establish them as a serious competitor in the industry.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1922, the company created an automatic punch recorder designed to record system status changes by punching holes in ticker tape.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1933, Autocall purchased the Howe Manufacturing Company of Chicago, Illinois and used their proprietary transmitter design to produce the Autocall-Howe system, a high-end fire alarm system targeted at large institutions and industrial plants.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] By the 1960s, Autocall-Howe systems were installed in many of the United States' largest factories, airports, and universities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Starting in the mid-1960s, Autocall began transitioning all of their fire alarm systems to solid state technology.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1970, the company produced the NA series of fire alarm systems which utilized modular components driven by printed circuit boards instead of traditional hardwired relays.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1973, Autocall invented the first voice evacuation system, followed by a firefighter's communication system in 1974.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] These technologies were OEM distributed to numerous other fire alarm companies who did not yet produce their own.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1977, Autocall introduced Auto Monitor, an entirely solid-state multiplex system that utilized remote transponders to distribute IDC's and other connections.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] These transponders could handle up to 8 points and remained in production for several years thereafter.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] A year later, the company introduced the Auto Command, a remote microprocessor-controlled command center with built-in printer.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] The Auto Monitor interpreted network command centers as transponders on the multiplex loop.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Shortly thereafter, the company introduced custom designed rackmount systems which had to be factory programmed for each client.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Due to the rapidly growing clientele and increased complexity of programs, Autocall brought field programmability to its multiplex systems in the mid-1980s.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1987, Autocall introduced a smaller series of one-loop field-programmable addressable systems for a burgeoning market of mid-size addressable applications.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1989, Autocall introduced the first color touchscreen graphic annunciator, known as Autograph.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1990, the company replaced the aging Auto Command II system with the AL-1500, a modern system capable of over 4,000 points.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 1990, the company was bought by Wormald International which then sold the company to Thorn Security.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Under the name "Thorn/Autocall", the company produced the TFX-series addressable panels and C-series conventional panels, which were rebrands of the Silent Knight SK-series conventional panels of the time.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] When Thorn was purchased by Tyco-owned Grinnell in 1996, their systems were branded under "Grinnell/Autocall".
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 2001, Tyco purchased Simplex Time Recorder Company and merged it with Grinnell, forming SimplexGrinnell.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Tyco retained the Autocall trademark, but the brand name went unused until Tyco merged with Johnson Controls on September 6, 2016.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] In 2017, Johnson Controls relaunched Autocall as a subsidiary brand.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Autocall markets a complete line of Simplex manufactured fire protection products to independent dealers.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] Autocall, along with Simplex, offers addressable notification appliances known as TrueAlert ES.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] These notification appliances are capable of reducing wiring, undergoing "self testing", strobe candela choice from the FACP, and make it easy to add new signals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/autocall] This line includes the regular horn/strobes, multi tone horn/strobes capable of outputting a 520 Hz Low Frequency tone for sleeping areas, outdoor signals, speaker/strobes, and LED devices.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] A **fire alarm notification appliance**, often simply called a **fire alarm**, is an active fire protection component of a fire alarm system.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] A notification appliance may use audible, visible, or other stimuli to alert the occupants of a fire or other emergency condition requiring action.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Audible appliances have been in use longer than any other method of notification.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Initially, all appliances were either electromechanical horns or electric bells, which would later be replaced by electronic sounders.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Most of today's appliances produce sound levels between 80 and 100 decibels at 3 ft (1 m).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] The primary function of the notification appliance is to alert persons at risk.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Several methods are used and documented in industry specifications published by UL.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Coding refers to the pattern or tones a notification appliance sounds in and is controlled either by the panel or by setting jumpers or DIP switches on the notification appliances.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] The majority of audible notification appliances installed prior to 1996 produced a steady sound for evacuation.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] In general, no common standard at that time mandated any particular tone, or pattern for audible fire alarm evacuation signals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] While less common than a steady sound, differing signaling methods were used for the same purpose.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] These are named with respect to their distinctive structure and include, March Time (usually 120 pulses per minute but sometimes at 90 pulses or 20 pulses per minute, depending on the panel), Hi-Lo (two different tones that alternate), Slow-Whoop (slow rising sweep upwards in tone) among others.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Today these methods are confined to applications intended to trigger a response other than evacuation alone.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] In 1996, the ANSI and the NFPA recommended a standard evacuation pattern to eliminate confusion.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] The pattern is uniform without regard to the sound used.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] CO (carbon monoxide) detectors are specified to use a similar pattern using four pulses of tone (often referred to as T4).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] In 1970, Space Age Electronics introduced the first visual notification appliance, the AV32 light plate (which was installed over an existing horn) and V33 remote light.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Meanwhile, in 1976, Wheelock introduced the first horn/strobe notification appliances with its 7000 series.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] The majority of visual signals throughout the 1970s and 1980s were white or red incandescent lights.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] In the 1980s, most new installations began to include visual signals, and more strobes started to appear.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] In the United States, the 1990 Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) triggered changes in evacuation signaling methods to include the hearing impaired.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Audible notification appliances would now have to include strobe lights with higher brightness intensity to alert the hearing impaired.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] This made incandescent lights inadequate for the purposes of the ADA.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Many existing installations that did not include visual signals were retrofitted with strobe plates.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] These retrofit plates would allow for the easy installation of a strobe without replacing the audible signal.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Later, ADA codes also required that strobes be at least 15 candelas and have a flash rate of at least 60 flashes per minute (one flash per second).
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Companies discontinued their translucent strobes, and replaced them with new, clear, high-intensity strobes.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Today, strobe synchronization is often used to synchronize all strobes in a uniform flash pattern.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] This is to prevent individuals with photosensitive epilepsy from potentially experiencing seizures due to unsynchronized strobes.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] In Europe, voice evacuation systems are normally a mandatory requirement for rail and air transport terminals, high-rise buildings, schools, hospitals, and other large facilities.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Voice systems for emergency use date back at least as far as the second world war.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Following the lead of companies like Avalon, Tannoy and Millbank Electronics etc., in the 1980s many other companies began producing voice-evacuation systems.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] In the 1990s, voice evacuation started to become the standard for large facilities, and is still growing in popularity.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] The use, design, operation and installation of Voice evacuation systems is governed in Europe by CENELEC European Committee for Electrotechnical Standardization EN 60849 and in the UK by the British Standard BS 5839-Part 8, a system code of practice.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] This is joined by the European harmonised equipment standards family EN 54, and ISO 7240-16:2007.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Initial research into the effectiveness of the various alerting methods is sparse.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] From 2005 to 2007, research sponsored by the NFPA focused on understanding the cause of a higher number of deaths seen in high-risk groups such as the elderly, those with hearing loss, and those who are intoxicated.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Research findings suggest that a mid frequency (520 Hz) square wave output is significantly more effective at waking high-risk individuals.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] More recent research suggests that strobe lights are not effective at waking sleeping adults with hearing loss and suggest that a different alarm tone is much more effective.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Individuals in the hearing loss community are seeking changes to improved awakening methods.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Further NFPA research demonstrated the heightened waking effectiveness of mid frequency square wave auditory signals that use 520 Hz, especially when used to wake people with mild to moderately severe hearing loss.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Two separate studies were conducted – one for the hard-of-hearing and one for the alcohol-impaired – in order to compare the waking effectiveness of 520 Hz mid frequency square wave devices and 3,100 Hz pure tone T-3 sound devices.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Under the testing conditions, a 520 Hz square wave T-3 sound woke up 92% of hard-of-hearing participants, making it the most effective.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] The 3100 Hz pure tone T-3 sound woke up 56% of participants.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] A summary of the studies shows that the 520 Hz square wave signal has at least 4 to 12 times more waking effectiveness than the current 3,100 Hz signal.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] Effective January 1, 2014, section 18.4.5.3 of the 2010 and later editions of NFPA 72 requires the mid frequency audible fire alarm signal in occupancy sleeping areas with a protected premises (building) fire alarm system.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] The Chapter 18 committee chose to apply the requirement to all sleeping areas – not just those where occupants have self-identified as having a hearing impairment.
[src:fire-alarm-notification-appliance/fire-alarm-notification-appliance] This was done intentionally for several reasons: in many cases, the applications impacted are lodging spaces such as hotels, and many people may not know they have a hearing impairment or they may be alcohol impaired.
